<Base title="honeymcp - open-source honeypot for MCP servers">
  <p class="post-meta">project · live on a Singapore VPS</p>

  <h1>What attackers actually send to MCP servers.</h1>

  <p>
    <strong>honeymcp</strong> is an open-source honeypot that impersonates a legitimate
    MCP (Model Context Protocol) server and logs every request it receives. It is written
    in Rust, runs anywhere Docker does, and is built to generate a public corpus of
    real-world attacks against the AI agent stack.
  </p>

  <p>
    The ecosystem has plenty of preventive tooling - gateways, classifiers, proxies.
    What it does not have is a public feed of what attackers actually send to MCP
    servers in the wild. <a href="/blog/">The blog</a> tracks the build, the captures,
    and the analysis as they happen.
  </p>

  <h2>What ships</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><code>honeymcp</code> - the sensor. JSON-RPC 2.0 over stdio or HTTP+SSE. Three built-in personas.</li>
    <li><code>honeymcp-probes</code> - 13-payload audit CLI for any MCP endpoint. <code>--fail-on-critical</code> as a CI gate.</li>
    <li>Seven threat detectors: prompt injection, shell injection, recon, tool enumeration, secret exfil, supply-chain config injection, unicode anomaly.</li>
    <li>SQLite + JSONL structured logging with remote address, User-Agent, and X-Forwarded-For capture.</li>
    <li>Live dashboard at <code>/dashboard</code> and JSON metrics at <code>/stats</code>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Install</h2>

  <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/kosiorkosa47/honeymcp
cd honeymcp
docker compose up -d
curl http://localhost:8080/healthz</code></pre>

  <p>
    Deployment guide, persona format, and probe catalog live in the
    <a href="https://github.com/kosiorkosa47/honeymcp" target="_blank" rel="noopener">repo</a>.
  </p>

